"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783158","Home Office","false","2017-11-20","<p>Intelligence and information on child criminal exploitation is collected at individual force level and Merseyside Police will hold the relevant information. At a national level, the National Crime Agency (NCA) is responsible for producing a national threat assessment on county lines based on information provided by individual forces and Regional Organised Crime Units and this includes child criminal exploitation. The next national threat assessment by the NCA is due to be published very shortly.</p><p> </p><p>We are taking firm action to tackle the issue of child criminal exploitation and county lines this includes: publishing new guidance for practitioners on identifying county lines and helping those being exploited; funding a pilot service for exploited young people caught up in county lines drugs running; match-funding local reviews to build resilience in areas where there are concerns about county lines; and we will be shortly implementing new powers to enable the police to close down mobile phone numbers that are being used to deal drugs as part of the county lines model.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2017-11-20T17:29:02.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783158/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783158/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-03","Organised Crime: Merseyside","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of trends in the level of child exploitation by criminal gangs across Merseyside.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","111303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783159","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Government published its assessment of the impacts of the alcohol duty changes in the Tax Information and Impact Note, which can be found online at:</p><p> </p><p><strong><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/alcohol-duty-rate-changes/alcohol-duty-rate-changes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/alcohol-duty-rate-changes/alcohol-duty-rate-changes</a> </strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-11-13T15:35:13.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783159/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783159/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-03","Beer: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the rise in beer duty in the March 2017 Budget (a) on the price of beer for consumers and (b) in tax revenue.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","111352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783160","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-13","<p>The apprenticeship levy was introduced in April 2017. Given that skills policy is devolved, devolved administrations will receive a population share of the UK-wide revenue from the levy. In 2017-18, the Welsh Government will receive £128 million, meaning they are receiving their fair share of the Levy.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-11-13T14:02:44.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783160/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783160/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-03","Apprentices: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much funding the Welsh Government has received from the apprenticeship levy in the first year of its implementation.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","111338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783161","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-13","<p>The UK government provides the Welsh Government with a population share of the Office for Budget Responsibility’s (OBR’s) apprenticeship levy forecast from March 2016. This means the Welsh Government will receive £128m in 2017-18, £133m in 2018-19, and £138m in 2019-20. Beyond 2019-20, once the levy is embedded, the normal operation of the Barnett Formula will continue to provide a population-based share of funding.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-11-13T14:04:03.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783161/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783161/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-03","Apprentices: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how the amount allocated to the Welsh Assembly under the apprenticeship levy is calculated.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","111339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783162","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Government is committed to improving access to financial services.</p><p> </p><p>The Access to Banking Standard, launched in May 2017, commits banks to ensure personal and business customers are better informed about branch closures and the reasons for them closing, along with the options they have locally to continue to access banking services, including specialist assistance for customers who need more help. The Access to Banking Standard is monitored and enforced by the independent Lending Standards Board.</p><p> </p><p>95% of banks’ business customers are now able to withdraw cash, deposit cash and cheques, and make balance enquiries at a Post Office counter via its network of 11,600 branches. Government will have provided nearly £2 billion during the period 2011 to 2018 to maintain and modernise the Post Office network.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-11-13T13:57:30.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783162/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783162/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-03","Bank Services: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 2 November 2017 to Question 109593, what representations he has made to representatatives of the banking sector on the accessibility of full banking services for SMEs when their bank branch closes.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783163","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-13","<p>It is not possible to produce meaningful estimates of the amount of levy payments made by employers in specific geographical areas. HMRC have information on where PAYE schemes are registered, though not on the workplaces of the employer. Many large employers will have various workplaces across the UK or outsource their payroll to a payroll provider based in a different location.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-11-13T14:05:41.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783163/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783163/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-03","Apprentices: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much apprenticeship levy funding has been collected in Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","111337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783164","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) has published an interim summary of the independent review of Royal Bank of Scotland’s treatment of small and medium-sized enterprise customers transferred to its Global Restructuring Group. The FCA announced it is investigating the matters arising from the review and focussing on whether there is any basis for it to take further action. It would not be appropriate for the Government to comment further whilst this process is ongoing.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-11-13T13:55:08.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783164/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783164/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-03","Royal Bank of Scotland: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he expects the further report of the Financial Conduct Authority on Royal Bank of Scotland's treatment of small and medium-sized enterprises to be published.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783165","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government is committed to extending the regulatory perimeter only where there is a clear case for doing so, in order to avoid putting additional costs on lenders that would ultimately lead to higher costs for businesses.</p><p> </p><p>However, unincorporated sole traders and small partnerships borrowing less than £25,000 do receive regulatory protection. In practice, the effect of this is that the smallest SMEs are more likely than not to receive regulatory protections when borrowing.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-11-07T14:53:11.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783165/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783165/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-03","Business: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 2 November 2017 to Question 110240 on the Royal Bank of Scotland, what plans he has to extend the responsibilities of the Financial Conduct Authority to oversee business lending.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783166","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-13","5% of last year’s Departmental spend (November 2016 to October 2017) with third-party suppliers was with Government strategic suppliers.<p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-11-13T15:30:31.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783166/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783166/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-03","Treasury: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of his Department's spend in the last year has been with Government strategic suppliers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","111291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783167","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-13","<p>The allocation of police funding between forces is led by the Home Office, and Police and Crime Commissioners are responsible for making decisions about how this funding is used to best address local needs. We have protected overall police spending in real terms. Since 2015 Police and Crime Commissioners will see their budgets maintained at cash levels so long as local council tax precept is maximised.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-11-13T14:01:06.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783167/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783167/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-03","Organised Crime: Merseyside","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions his Department has had with the Home Secretary on police funding to tackle gun crime and serious and organised crime across Merseyside.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","111308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783168","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-13","<p>In line with the published Crown Representatives and Strategic Suppliers List, the Department’s proportion of procurement spend with strategic suppliers for financial year 2016-17 was 14 per cent as shown on our records.</p><p>AMEY COMMUNITY LTD</p><p>ATKINS LTD</p><p>BT PAYMENT SERVICES LTD</p><p>CAPITA</p><p>CGI IT UK LTD</p><p>FUJITSU SERVICES LTD</p><p>INTERSERVE</p><p>ORACLE CORPORATION UK LTD</p><p>VODAFONE</p><p>The Crown Representatives and Strategic Suppliers list is shown at the website below.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/strategic-suppliers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/strategic-suppliers</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-11-13T17:14:29.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783168/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783168/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-03","Department for Communities and Local Government: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of his Department's spend in the last year has been with Government strategic suppliers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","111279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783169","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-13","<p>The table below shows how much the Department for Communities and Local Government Arm’s Length Bodies and Non Departmental Public Bodies have spent on employees partly or wholly employed on trade union duties in each year since 2015.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>FY - 2015/16</p></td><td><p>FY - 2016/17</p></td><td><p>FY - 2017/18</p></td><td><p>Accumulative total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Planning Inspectorate (PINS)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£19,111.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£14,173.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£5948.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£39,232.00</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Homes and Communities Agency (HCA)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£17,579.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£20,660.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£17,399.55</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£55,638.55</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>*Valuation Tribunal Service</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£119.25</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£120.45</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£239.70</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>QE11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Lease</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Ebbsfleet</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£0.00</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Individual support to Unison members has been provided via their Regional Officer, which has meant that the costs have predominately fallen on Unison not the VTS.</p><p>In addition, Housing Ombudsman has two union representatives that are released on an ad hoc basis for trade union activities. The cost is not centrally recorded.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-11-13T17:10:41.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783169/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783169/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-03","Department for Communities and Local Government: Trade Union Officials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much his Department's public bodies spent on employees partly or wholly employed on trade union duties in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","111400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783170","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-05","<p>The cost of a) fraud and b) error to the Department and its agencies is zero, since all identified fraud losses have been recovered subsequently. In the instances of 'error', which is generally caused by internal employee payment issues, the Department recovers these losses through payroll so there is no outstanding cost to the Department or its agencies to report.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-12-05T17:04:00.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783170/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783170/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-03","Department for Communities and Local Government: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the cost of (a) fraud and (b) financial error in (i) his Department, (ii) its executive agencies and (iii) its non-departmental public bodies in each year from 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","111401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783171","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Department plans to carry out a review of selective licensing shortly. The review will be informed partly by the progress and outcomes on a number of applications for large scale schemes submitted in the second half of this year, which is why the start of the review has been deferred.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-13T17:31:21.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783171/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783171/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-03","Rented Housing: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Oral contribution of Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 23 March 2015, Official Report, column GC331, what progress has been made on undertaking a review of the impact of changes to the selective licensing of houses; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","111411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783172","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-13","<p>The information on Government’s capital expenditures on affordable housing through Government’s affordable homes programmes is available publicly.</p><p>A summary of housing expenditure under the Housing Corporation for the period 2000 - 2008 and the National Affordable Homes Programme 2008-11 is available through the National Archives website:</p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20071204140632/http:/www.housingcorp.gov.uk" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20071204140632/http://www.housingcorp.gov.uk</a></p><p>For the Affordable Homes Programme 2011-2015:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/affordable-homes-programme-2011-to-2015-guidance-and-allocations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/affordable-homes-programme-2011-to-2015-guidance-and-allocations</a></p><p>For the Affordable Homes Programme 2015-2018:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2015-to-2018-quarterly-updates" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2015-to-2018-quarterly-updates</a></p><p>For the Shared Ownership and Affordable Homes Programme 2016-21:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2016-to-2021-successful-bidders" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2016-to-2021-successful-bidders</a></p><p>Data for London only is available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.london.gov.uk/about-us/london-assembly/london-assembly-committees/budget-monitoring-sub-committee" target="_blank">http://www.london.gov.uk/about-us/london-assembly/london-assembly-committees/budget-monitoring-sub-committee</a></p><p><a href="https://www.london.gov.uk/about-us/governance-and-spending/spending-money-wisely/annual-accounts-and-governance-statement" target="_blank">https://www.london.gov.uk/about-us/governance-and-spending/spending-money-wisely/annual-accounts-and-governance-statement</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-13T17:06:51.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783172/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783172/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-03","Affordable Housing: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the affordable housing budget was in each of the last 15 years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","111424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783173","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-09","<p>We do not collect data on forecast job numbers for Enterprise Zones and do not publish estimates for net additional jobs.</p><p>Enterprise Zones are a twenty five year programme to support local economic growth, helping businesses to expand and ensure there is the high quality office and industrial space needed for them to do so. Local Enterprise Partnerships report that since 2012 and up to September 2016, Enterprise Zones had attracted over 822 businesses and more than £3.3 billion in private investment.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-11-09T14:37:21.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783173/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783173/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-03","Job Creation: Enterprise Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 30 October 2017 to Question 108119, on job creation: enterprise zones, how many jobs enterprise zones were planned to create in each year since 2013.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","111426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783174","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-13","<p>Findings from the national evaluation will be published in the Troubled Families Programme’s annual report.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-11-13T17:28:56.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783174/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783174/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-03","Families: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 30 October 2017 to Question 108916, on families: disadvantaged, what the specified interval periods will be for reporting on the national evaluation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","111427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783175","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-13","<p>The decision to make the current Troubled Families Programme (2015-2020) subject to a comprehensive national evaluation was made in October 2014, by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-11-13T17:14:58.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783175/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783175/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-03","Families: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 30 October 2017 to Question 108916, on families: disadvantaged, when the decision was made to make the troubled families programme subject to a comprehensive national evaluation; and which Minister made that decision.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","111428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783176","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-13","<p>The report and recommendations of the Private Rented Sector Electrical Safety Standards Working Group has been published online at the link below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/electrical-safety-standards-in-the-private-rented-sector-working-group-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/electrical-safety-standards-in-the-private-rented-sector-working-group-report</a></p><p>The Working Group report draws together the views and opinions expressed by group members at each of the working group meetings.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-13T16:53:39.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783176/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783176/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-03","Private Rented Housing: Electrical Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 1 November 2017 to Question 109734, on private rented housing: safety, if he will publish the minutes of the working group on electrical safety in the private rented sector.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","111442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783177","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-13","<p>The majority of local authorities provide annual data returns to the Department on how they use the Disabled Facilities Grant to provide adaptations to the homes of older and disabled people. While the data provides the best estimate currently available of the number of adaptations installed, the Government is aware that there are some limitations, for example, due to the local authority response rate not being 100 per cent and some differing interpretations of questions used to collect the data.</p><p>The Government does not currently produce data on the Disabled Facilities Grant. However, the Department provides local authority returns to <em>Foundations</em>, the Government-funded national body for home improvement agencies. <em>Foundations</em> analyses the data to understand Disabled Facilities Grant delivery nationally.</p><p>From records provided by <em>Foundations</em>, the data shows that the following numbers of adaptations, funded through the Disabled Facilities Grant, were delivered from 2012-13 to 2016-17:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of DFG-funded adaptations delivered</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>42,125</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>42,770</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>40,645</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>40,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>49,000*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Estimated total to 2016-17</p></td><td><p>215,340</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>Data returns expected October 2018</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*estimate on the basis of local authority returns received to date.</p><p>As in excess of 40,000 adaptations have been funded each year by the Disabled Facilities Grant, we anticipate the total number of adaptations to be around 250,000 by the end of the 2017-18 financial year.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-13T16:49:45.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783177/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783177/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-03","Social Rented Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 1 November 2017 to Question 109733, on social rented housing: disability, how many adaptations were completed in each year since 2012-13.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","111441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783178","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-13","<p>On 6 October, Openreach published details of the key elements of the offer which are available here (<a href="https://www.openreach.co.uk/orpg/home/updates/downloads/Deliveringuniversalbroadbandcoverage.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.openreach.co.uk/orpg/home/updates/downloads/Deliveringuniversalbroadbandcoverage.pdf</a>) . The Department is currently considering two approaches for delivering universal broadband - a regulatory USO and BT's voluntary proposal. A decision will be made in due course on which approach to follow.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-11-13T13:39:17.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783178/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783178/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-03","Broadband: Universal Service Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if the Government will publish the full description of BT's voluntary offer to deliver the Universal Service Obligation for broadband, the Government's response to that offer and the timetable for the release of those publications.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","111397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783179","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-13","<p>We are committed to ensuring there are sustainable business models for high quality news media as set out in the manifesto, and this includes the local and regional press. In particular, government recognises that local and regional news outlets have been hit by falling print circulations and the shift of advertising online.</p><p>We have been holding meetings with industry representatives to explore these issues which form one aspect of the work underway to develop the Digital Charter.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-11-13T13:33:30.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783179/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783179/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-03","Local Press","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 30 October 2017 to Question 109291, if she will collect information on the number of local newspapers across the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","111297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783180","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-13","<p>In 2016-17, the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport spent 17.6% of its procurement with the Government strategic suppliers.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-11-13T17:52:21.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783180/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783180/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-03","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of her Department's spend in the last year has been with Government strategic suppliers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","111281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783181","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-13","<p>We recognise the importance of the permanent preservation of archives for long-term public benefit by museums, galleries, archives and libraries. The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) and the Data Protection Bill permit such organisations to process personal data (including sensitive personal data) without consent, where necessary for “archiving purposes in the public interest”, subject to appropriate safeguards for the rights and freedoms of data subjects. It also exempts archiving services from complying with certain rights of data subjects (for example, rights to access, rectify or erase their data), where the exercise of such rights would seriously impair or prevent them from fulfilling their objectives.</p><p> </p><p>‘Archiving in the public interest’ is a new term in data protection law. The Data Protection Act 1998 made no express reference to it and it is not defined in the GDPR, but Recital 158 to the GDPR may help to understand it. It says:</p><p> </p><p>“Public authorities or public or private bodies that hold records of public interest should be services which, pursuant to Union or Member State law, have a legal obligation to acquire, preserve, appraise, arrange, describe, communicate, promote, disseminate and provide access to records of enduring public value for general public interest.”</p><p> </p><p>This is likely to apply to a wide variety of community, private, public sector, charitable/trust and voluntary sector archives. It could also include archives that may be closed to researchers at the present time, but which would become accessible at some future date, and archives which are held in analogue or digital format. The definition would not, however, cover organisations which gather and use data, information and records purely for their own commercial gain or that have no enduring public value.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that concerns have been raised about the reference in the Recital to archiving organisations being under a ‘legal obligation’ to archive. While this may reflect the archival system in some other EU member states, it does not reflect the position in the UK. Many smaller archives, particularly in the private sector, are unlikely to have any statutory obligations to archive.</p><p> </p><p>We do not think the best approach is to create new statutory duties requiring organisations to archive. This could force organisations to archive that had no intention or means of doing so. Instead, we want to reassure bona fide archiving services that they will be able to continue to process personal data for the purposes of archiving in the public interest, regardless of whether they have a statutory obligation to do so. The reasons for this are:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Recitals act as explanatory notes to European regulations and have no direct legal effect. They may be taken into account by regulators and the courts when interpreting and applying the law, but they are not the law.</li><li>In any event Recital 158 should be read in conjunction with Recital 41 which says that “where this regulation refers to a legal basis or legislative measure, this does not necessarily require a legislative act adopted by a parliament”, providing that such a legal basis is clear and precise and its application is foreseeable to persons subject to it.</li><li>In the UK, most archives operate on a permissive basis under the general provisions of common law or statutory permissive powers, such as the British Library Act 1972 or the Local Government (Records) Act 1962. It may be open to organisations to rely on such a basis to satisfy the requirements of Recital 158.</li><li>Where there are no clear permissive powers, organisations may still be able to point to funding agreements, management agreements or constitutional documents which set out the purposes of the archive, particularly if the failure to adhere to such purposes could have legal or quasi-legal effects, for example for a body’s charitable status. Although this may not amount to a statutory obligation to archive, it would give organisations a legal basis upon which to rely.</li><li>Up until now, organisations responsible for archiving may have relied on exemptions from subject access rights under the ‘historical research’ provisions in section 33 of the Data Protection Act 1998. These provisions will continue in the new Data Protection Bill, and have not been abolished by GDPR. Most of the exemptions from data subjects’ rights in relation to archiving also exist in relation to historical research. If archiving services cannot confidently rely on the exemptions for archiving in the public interest, they may be able to rely on exemptions for historical research as an alternative. We recognise that there is some debate about this point within the sector because some archives may not exist for historical research purposes. In that case, a legal basis for archiving will be needed, but it does not need to be statutory.</li></ul>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-11-13T18:35:30.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783181/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783181/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-03","Archives: Public Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what definition her Department uses for the phrase archiving in the public interest.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","111381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783182","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Government does not intend to reintroduce defined Public Library Service Standards (PLSS), which were were withdrawn along with other government imposed performance targets in a move towards increased local autonomy.</p><p> </p><p>In September 2017, the Libraries Taskforce made available a new sector-led benchmarking framework for library services in England, developed with the Local Government Association, to enable library services to self-assess, develop and improve.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-11-13T14:08:16.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783182/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783182/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-03","Public Libraries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans she has to reintroduce public library standards.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","111382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783183","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-13","<p>Libraries play an important role in giving everyone opportunities to improve their life chances and achieve their full potential.</p><p> </p><p>In recognition of this, the Government funds the Libraries Taskforce to deliver its 2016 strategy Libraries Deliver. DCMS is also investing £3.9 million in the Libraries: Opportunities for Everyone fund to support innovative library service activity in 2017/18 to benefit disadvantaged people and places in England.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-11-13T14:09:53.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783183/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783183/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-03","Public Libraries: Social Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment she has made of the importance of libraries to social mobility.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","111383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783184","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-13","<p>Local authorities in England have a statutory duty under the Public Libraries and Museums Act 1964 to provide a comprehensive and efficient library service. It is therefore for each local authority to determine how best to provide a public library service that meets local needs and within available resources.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport monitors developments relating to proposed changes to library services in England. The Government is working with the Libraries Taskforce to promote good practice and innovation to assist library services and enable them to be sustainable for the long term.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-11-13T14:12:06.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783184/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783184/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-03","Public Libraries: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the effect of library closures on local communities.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","111384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783185","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-13","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 23 October 2017 to Question 107787 to the hon. Member for Kingston Upon Hull North (Diana Johnson).</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-11-13T17:18:10.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783185/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783185/answer","20171023_107787_WQnA-extract_on_Military_Aircraft.docx","107787 - WQnA extract on Military Aircraft","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783185/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-03","Hawk Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to place new orders for Hawk Trainers for the Royal Air Force.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","111375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783186","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-09","<p>In financial year 2016-17, Ministry of Defence total expenditure with Government strategic suppliers was £7.8 billion. This amounts to 32.4% of the Department's overall spend on goods and services.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-11-09T14:35:02.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783186/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783186/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-03","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of his Department's spend in the last year has been with Government strategic suppliers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","111280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783187","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Defence Secretary and Ministry of Defence Ministers meet with the Director General Defence Safety Authority (DG DSA) routinely. DG DSA meets the Defence Secretary twice a year and the Minister for Defence Personnel and Veterans quarterly or more often. These meetings cover all aspects of safety in Defence which may include, but are not limited to, discussions relating to fire safety at military bases.</p><p>The former Defence Secretary, as a member of The Defence Board, was briefed by DG DSA on his Annual Assurance Report, which includes content relating to fire safety.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-11-13T17:21:54.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783187/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783187/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-03","Military Bases: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 30 October 2017 to Question 109676, on military bases: fire prevention, on how many occasions a Minister from his Department has met the Director General Defence Safety Authority to discuss fire safety at military bases in the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","111425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783188","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-13","<p>Like any large organisation we allocate funds to those activities that are the highest priority. The Dreadnought submarine replacement programme will provide the ultimate guarantee of our national security - it remains within its budget.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-11-13T17:21:10.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783188/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783188/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-03","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether any additional funds will be allocated to the Trident replacement programme in the 2017-18 financial year which have not already been budgeted for.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","111415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783189","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-13","<p>We recognise the important contribution the UK's Defence Aerospace Industry makes to the UK's national security and prosperity.</p><p>Through the Future Combat Air Strategy Technology Initiative (FCAS TI), announced as part of the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review settlement, we are pursuing a national programme to ensure the UK retains the skills and capabilities necessary to maintain our place as a global leader in this area including in the wider supply chain.</p><p>We continue to review the defence industrial landscape, including in the UK aerospace sector to better understand our longer-term requirements and delivery options including the potential for international partnering, industry's appetite to invest, adjacent civil investment and overall affordability. Our review process considers the broader supply chain and will be taken into consideration in future procurement decisions. In addition, the refreshed Defence Industrial Policy will further explain how our investment choices take account of factors contributing to a more dynamic and productive UK economy, in which the UK defence supply chain plays a crucial part.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-11-13T17:18:55.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783189/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783189/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-03","Military Aircraft: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if his Department will give consideration to retaining UK aerospace design and manufacturing capability by taking into account supply chains when purchasing new aircraft.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","111413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783190","Department for Education","false","2017-11-13","<p>Families can play a significant role in supporting prisoners, as studies show that positive relationships are an important factor in reducing reoffending. The government has taken the following action to improve support for prisoners and their families:</p><ul><li>Funded a contract worth over £1.4m for Barnardo’s to operate the i-HOP service to share evidence on practice and advise commissioners and practitioners on the options available to support the families of offenders.</li><li>Given prison governors the budget and flexibility to spend their resources as they see fit to help prisoners establish or maintain important family and significant other ties.</li><li>Awarded a new contract for family services across the female estate in October 2017, allowing women’s prisons to work closely with a single professional family services provider, to develop innovative support solutions.</li><li>Enabled better communication between prisoners and their families through the facilitation of organised and constructive family days, as well as courses and programmes to promote parenting and family engagement.</li><li>Women’s prisons also work to provide other support for improved family links, including family days, child-centred visits, homework clubs and specific relationship and parenting skills programmes.</li><li>Finally, we are building the evidence of what works for all children in need, investing £5 million to test targeted support to improve their outcomes.</li></ul>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-11-13T16:57:54.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783190/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783190/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-03","Mothers: Custodial Treatment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to develop an informed and co-ordinated range of child-centred services and support to ensure positive outcomes for the children of mothers serving short-term prison sentences.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","111404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783191","Department for Education","false","2017-11-13","<p>Average class size figures for state-funded schools in England are calculated and published annually in the statistical first releases available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers</a>.</p><p>A national summary of average class sizes for Key Stages 1 and 2 and secondary is in each national tables document, tables 6a and 6b respectively.</p><p>A summary at local authority and regional level is only available for Key Stages 1 and 2 and can be found in each local authority and regional tables document in table 11.</p><p>Data is not summarised by parliamentary constituency, but data for each school providing average class sizes for Key Stages 1 and 2, where appropriate, and overall is available via opening the underlying tables document for each year then via the file ‘…Schools_Classes_UD’. The figures can be filtered by parliamentary constituency, school phase and local authority.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-11-13T17:06:44.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783191/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783191/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-03","Class Sizes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of average class sizes in (a) Liverpool, Walton constituency, (b) the North West and (c) England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","111306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783192","Department for Education","false","2017-11-13","<p>The proportion of direct spend with government strategic suppliers as per the <em>Crown Representatives and Strategic Suppliers (September 2017)</em> list from Cabinet Office for 2016-17 is 0.3%.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-11-13T16:10:46.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783192/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783192/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-03","Department for Education: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of her Department's spend in the last year has been with Government strategic suppliers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","111282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783193","Department for Education","false","2017-11-13","<p>Following the review of the national curriculum, which concluded in 2013, teaching the history of the Holocaust remained a compulsory part of the history curriculum for maintained schools at key stage 3 (age 11 – 14). There is scope for schools to teach about the Holocaust at other key stages, in an age-appropriate way.</p><p>The Department funds the ‘Lessons from Auschwitz’ programme, which aims to increase knowledge and understanding of the Holocaust for young people.</p><p>In addition, jointly with the Pears Foundation, we fund University College London’s Centre for Holocaust Education, which will provide continuing professional development for over a thousand teachers in England this year.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-11-13T16:48:56.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783193/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783193/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-03","World War II: Genocide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans she has to add Holocaust education to all key stages of the national curriculum.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","111269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783194","Department for Education","false","2017-11-13","<p>Academy trusts are accountable to my Rt Hon. Friend the Secretary of State through her network of Regional Schools Commissioners (RSCs). RSCs work closely with local councils in driving forward school improvement in their areas</p><p> </p><p>In addition, all academy trusts are required to include two parent governors on their trust board or on each of the local governing bodies in their trusts.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-11-13T16:36:47.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783194/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783194/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-03","Academies: Accountability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what arrangements she has put in place to ensure local democratic accountability of multi-academy trusts.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","111272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783195","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-13","<p>In the financial year 2016/17, 13.1% of Defra’s total expenditure was with Government strategic suppliers.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-13T11:06:36.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783195/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783195/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-03","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of his Department's spend in the last year has been with Government strategic suppliers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","111283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783196","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-13","<p>The government regularly discusses the protection of geographical indications (GIs) at both ministerial and official levels with industry and relevant stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p>We are planning to use the EU (Withdrawal) Bill to transfer into domestic law the EU schemes that currently protect our GIs. This will ensure that UK GIs which are already registered remain protected in the UK after we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Future protection for current UK GIs in EU member states, and for EU GIs in the UK, is subject to negotiations with the EU. Producers outside the EU are already able to participate in the EU's GI schemes when selling onto the EU market. In the same way, after we leave the EU new UK GIs will be able to apply for protection under the EU GI scheme.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-13T17:21:21.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783196/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783196/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-03","Food: Origin Marking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what representations his Department has received on whether placing geographical indicators for products on a UK legal basis through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will mean that those indicators are recognised by EU member states; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","111369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783197","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Government will set out plans for peat restoration in the 25 Year Environment Plan and an England Peat Strategy.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-11-13T10:20:39.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783197/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783197/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-03","Peat Bogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will publish his plans for peat restoration.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","111367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783198","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-13","<p>The Queen’s Speech announced that an Agriculture Bill would be introduced during this session of Parliament. The Bill will allow us to deliver our manifesto commitment to provide stability to farmers as we leave the EU, supporting the industry to compete domestically and on the global market, and will allow us to grow more, sell more and export more great British food.</p><p> </p><p>We are working with industry and other interested parties to discuss the shape of future policy but we have also been clear that there will be a transition from one system to the next.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-13T16:43:19.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783198/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783198/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-03","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what his Department's timetable is for the introduction of a new farm policy.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","111351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783199","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-08","<p>Since 2014, we have invested in improving border security by recruiting new inspectors, enhancing training provision and facilitating closer working with Border Force. This additional investment has allowed the UK to increase its risk based inspections on goods which are not controlled at an EU level and therefore where mandatory inspections are not required. Uncontrolled trade inspections see relatively higher interception rates than inspections of controlled trades (15% vs 3%) and this data provides helpful intelligence and evidence to support new regulations and targeted monitoring.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-11-08T17:56:15.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783199/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783199/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-03","Trees: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 24 October 2017 to Question 108716, on trees: imports, for what reasons the UK intercepts a higher proportion of harmful organisms than other EU countries.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","111333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783200","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-14","<p>The Plant Health (England) Order 2015 and the Plant Health (Forestry) Order 2005 provide the statutory framework for preventing the introduction of pests and control action in the event of outbreaks and cover many harmful organisms affecting tree health. Similar legislation is in place in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Under the Orders the import of harmful organisms, plants and plant products that pose a serious plant health risk is prohibited. They also provide for additional measures to be introduced, including a ban on import, where new specific threats are identified or where existing measures have proved deficient.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-11-14T15:44:53.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783200/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783200/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783200/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-03","Trees: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 24 October 2017 to Question 108716, on trees: imports, what powers the UK Plant Health Authority has to ban imports of trees carrying harmful organisms.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","111334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783201","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-14","<p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade and I have regular contact with our US counterparts on a range of issues. However, we have had no discussions on Section 230 of the US Communications Decency Act 1996.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","111326","2017-11-14T16:36:57.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783201/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783201/answer","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783201/answer/previousversion/22068","Biography information for Greg Hands","202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-03","Internet: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with his US counterpart on section 230 of the US Communications Decency Act 1996.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","111325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783202","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-14","<p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade and I have regular contact with our US counterparts on a range of issues. However, we have had no discussions on Section 230 of the US Communications Decency Act 1996.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","111325","2017-11-14T16:36:57.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783202/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783202/answer","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783202/answer/previousversion/22067","Biography information for Greg Hands","202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-03","USA: Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what his policy is on the potential inclusion of section 230 of the US Communications Decency Act 1996 in any US-UK free trade deal.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","111326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783203","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-13","<p>The process for The Gambia's re-entry into the Commonwealth is being led by the Commonwealth Secretariat. We have been consistent and vocal in our support. Our High Commission in Banjul met the Commonwealth Secretariat's assessment mission in September and is engaging with the Government and other member states' representatives on the ground as the process moves forward. We look forward to welcoming The Gambia to the Commonwealth Summit next year.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-11-13T14:38:13.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783203/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/783203/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-03","Gambia: Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to support The Gambia to rejoin the Commonwealth.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","111327"
